@node LOADUP " SuperLeagueV3.51 Guide - Loading details "

@{b}Step-by-Step guide to loading :@{ub}

	1) Load Workbench from either floppy or hard disk
	2) Open up the SuperLeague disk icon.
	3) Open up the SuperLeague3.51 drawer icon.
	4) Double-click on the SuperLeague V3.51 icon.
	5) Wait while SuperLeague loads

If you have any loading problems you should try and isolate the problem -
the ideal way to do this is by using the excellent PD program @{b}SnoopDOS by
Eddy Carroll@{ub} before you start to load SuperLeague and keep and eye out to
see if there are any @{b}"Fail"@{ub} reports in the right hand column. If problems
persist you should @{"contact the author" link CONTACT} , Edward Burcher.
@endnode
@node UPTODATE " SuperLeagueV3.51 Guide - Bringing a League up to date "
    Due to the comprehensive amount of data stored by SuperLeagueV3.51,
going from a blank table to an up to date one if the league season is part
way through is a problem. You have 2 options : 

	(i) Input ALL the results up to that point in the season. This is 
OK if it has only been a couple of weeks since the start of the season and
you have records of all the results, but in the middle of a season it will
be impractical not to say masochistic.

	(ii) Forget about the season up to this point, as far as the
Favourite Team Features are concerned at least and just alter the table
(I will get to how you do this in a moment). This will mean that the table
will be correct but SuperLeague will not have a record of the favourite 
team's results up to this point or Goal Timings etc., so features like the
position graph and form guide will not have any data to work with up to that
point of the season. In effect, as far as those features are concerned, the
season will have just started but the table information will be correct.

Altering the Table Data : 

   Select @{"Preferences" link PREFS} from the first menu and click on the
@{b}'Special Team Data Correction Facility'@{ub} option. Now systematically
go through each team, updating it's data. When you are finished, return to 
the main prefs screen, select @{b}'Use'@{ub} and then save the league using
the @{"Save League" link SAVE} option from the first menu.
@endnode
@node DATAFILES " Technical Information - System Datafiles "

 This is provided so that if you get into difficulties, it may help to 
understand what is going on underneath the surface.

 There are 7 files comprising each league, and it is important that they all
work in harmony - and in particular that the main League Data File (No. 1)
which stores the table data stays in sync with all the Favourite team data
files  (No.s 2 3 4 5 6) that store all the extra data which allows features
such as the position graph and goal timings bar chart. This means that you
must not forget to use the @{"Save League" link SAVE} option after entering
some results.

 The files will become "out of sync" if you do not. If you enter a
favourite team result, the extra data you input about scorers and so on is
saved automatically to the data files (No.s 2 3 4 5 6).
So, if you were to forget to save before you quit, then the League Data
File on disk would still contain the old league data, but the new
scorers/goal timings information would have been saved to the data files.
Hence the files would be out of sync because, having realised your error,
if you tried to enter the results again, the extra data would be saved
AGAIN to the data files and so they would be inaccurate. If you make this
error there are 2 ways to correct it  :

	(i) Use the 'Special Data Correction Facility' and edit the
information for every team to the most recent table information, so that
the league table will be in sync with the data files. SAVE from the main
menu to make these changes permanent. This can be a tedious method and you
may find it quicker to use a text editor on the league data file (No 1) as
long as you know what you are doing.
	(ii) Similarly you could use a text editor to chop the relavent 
data off the end of the Favourite team data files (those found in the
Sysfiles directory) pertaining to this league. Then the data may be
reentered as normal.

As you can see, it can be a tricky task rectifying an error like this so 
don't make it !

1) The League Data File (stored in directory 'Leagues')
	i) What it does
		Stores Team names, number of games won/drawn/lost etc
		Also stores the names of the system files associated with
		that league.
		Also stores selected preferences data particular to this
		league : How many points for a win etc.
	ii) When it is accessed
		Whenever you select @{"Load" link LOAD} or @{"Save" link LOAD} options from menu one.
		 Because this file contains the pathnames of the other files
		 associated with the league it contains it is always the 
		 first file loaded.
	iii) Extra info
		Because it contains some preferences settings, this
		information will supersede the main preferences settings.

2) The Favourite Team Results Text file (stored in 'SysFiles' directory)

	i) What it does
		Stores the results of the favourite team in ASCII form, for
		 displaying in the @{"Favourite team results" link FAVE} option of menu 3
	ii) When it is accessed
		Loading from it takes place on selection of the
		 @{"Favourite team results" link FAVE} menu option.
		Saving to it occurs directly after specialist data has been
		 entered from the @{"Enter Results" link ENTER} screen, after a result of
		 the favourite team has been entered.

3) The Favourite Team Results Data file (stored in 'SysFiles' directory)
	
	i) What it does
		Stores the results of the favourite team in short form, for
		 processing the home/away records of the favourite team 
		 quickly
	ii) When it is Accessed
		At the same times as no.2 above

4) The Favourite Team Goal Timings Data file(stored in 'SysFiles' directory)

	i) What it does
		Stores the timings of the goals scored by the selected
		 favourite team.
	ii) When it is accessed
		Saved after specialist data entry from @{"Enter Results" link ENTER}
		 (as in no.s 2 & 3 above)
		Loading from it takes place on selection of the
		 @{"Goal Timings Graph" link BARCHART} option from menu 3.

5) The Form Guide Data file (stored in 'Sysfiles' directory)

	i) What it does
		Stores the last five results of the selected favourite team.
	ii) When it is accessed
		Saved after specialist data entry from @{"Enter Results" link ENTER}
		 (as in no.s 2,3 & 4 above)
		Loading from it occurs on selection of the
		 @{"Favourite Team Form" link FORM} option from menu 3.		

6) The League Position Data file (stored in 'Sysfiles' directory)
	
	i) What it does
		Stores the position of the favourite team after each result.
	ii) When it is accessed
		Saved to after specialist data entry from @{"Enter Results" link ENTER}
		 (as in no.s 2,3,4 & 5 above)
		Loading from it occurs on selection of the @{"Position Graph" link GRAPH}
		 option of menu 3.

7) The Cup Results file (stored in 'Cups' directory)

	i) What it does
		Stores all cup results for the Favourite team.
	ii) When it is accessed
		On selection of @{"Enter Cup Results" link CUP} option from menu 2
		Any disk access while in the Cup Results section of the
		 program will be to or from this file
	iii) Extra info
		This file and indeed the Cup results section is effectively
		 independent of the rest of the program and data. If you
		 weren't bothered about Cup results, then losing this file
		 would be of no great consequence.
@endnode
