@node INSTRINTRO "Instructions - Introduction"
	   
@{b}SuperLeague V3.51@{ub}  ©1992,1994 Edward A G Burcher
	            V3.51 updated July 1994

SuperLeague V3.51 is the result of many months AMOS Programming and 
extensive testing. Despite this, it may be that combinations of peripherals,
memory setups, etc. beyond my humble system may cause compatability problems
(At the time of writing I have a 1Mb A500(512K Chip) with 2nd disk drive.)
 
In such cases please @{"contact me" link CONTACT}, so that I can correct errors in future
releases. Also write if you have any bug reports or suggestions for new
features in future releases.

@{b}Important Notes:@{ub}

	SuperLeague can handle leagues with up to 26 teams using either
a two or three points for a win system. This is sufficient to maintain
most football leagues - Certainly the FA Premier, Football League 1,2 and 3
and Scotland / Italy / France etc. 

	In each Table, One team can be picked as the 'Favourites'. This
means you can follow your team via SuperLeague, as the selected 'Favourite'
has extra features including Goals Chart, Seasons Results (Including Scorers
and Goal Timings).
The Filenames handling these extra features are held in the 'SysFiles'
directory on disk and should not be relocated.
Similarly, The SL3Prefs.data file contains the saved preferences, and is
always held in the main SuperLeague drawer. This file MUST NOT be renamed
or moved.

@{b}Hard disk@{ub} users should click @{"here" link HARDDISK} for installation info.

@{b}WARNING :@{ub} SuperLeague requires @{b}1MB AT LEAST@{ub}, and although the current
version should run from Workbench even when the memory-consuming printer
software is active, you may need to run it from CLI without workbench being
open if memory is causing problems. Problems should not be experienced for
machines with more than 1Mb of memory but on a 1Mb amiga when using the
printer with SuperLeague, memory is tight and you should close all other
applications to avoid problems.

@{b}Procedure for CLI usage :@{ub}

  1) Reboot your Workbench disk
  2) Once the AmigaDOS window appears, press CTRL-D to interrupt the
      script execution.
  3) Move to the Superleague directory, using 'cd'. Eg. If the 
      SuperLeague disk is in an external drive df1: you would type
         cd df1:SuperLeague3.51 to change to the main SuperLeague directory.
  4) Type 'execute "SuperLeague V3.51"' to execute the startup script
      for SuperLeague3.51 (include the speech marks(") but not the
      apostrophes('))
@endnode
@node HARDDISK "Hard Disk Installation Procedure"

First, let me say that as I do not own a hard disk (lack of funds :-( - but
if anyone is willing to donate one...... ;-) ) so the perfection of a HD
installable version of SL3.51 has been tricky. I have tried to simulate it
by creating a portable version on floppy which can be moved into different
directories and still work, and this is what you are using.

N.B SuperLeagueV3.51 and its vastly superior sucessor V4.01 are both HD
installable, but previous releases to V3.51 are not HD installable. This
means that you cannot install V3.40, V3.41 or V3.50 to hard disk.

@{b}Installation Procedure :@{ub}
1) From Workbench, open the SuperLeague disk icon. Drag the drawer icon
"SuperLeague3.51" into the desired directory in your HD directory structure
All the files will then be copied across.

2) That's it !! Note that there appears to be some incompatability between
different versions of IconX. My 1.3 version appears not to have worked on 
an A1200 under 3.0 so I have made the icon paths refer to your c:iconx file.
This may mean that single drive users have a bit more swapping than they
might like, but with a bit of CLI knowledge and a bit of messing with the
info menu option from workbench, this could be improved. 

Note also that the script which launches SuperLeague via IconX reassigns
your fonts: assign. Unfortunately I could not think of a way to reassign it
to what it previously was at the end of the program, so it would be a good
idea to append the script file "SuperLeague V3.51" with a line to reassign
it. e.g if your usual font path is sys:fonts/ (as most people's is) then
just add the line :-
	@{b}assign fonts: sys:fonts/@{ub}
to the end of the script file.
@endnode
@node LOAD "Instructions - Load League"

   As it says just loads the league, along with assorted prefs specific to
that league , i.e. Favourite team in that league etc.
If the filename does not exist it will ask for another. Simply select Cancel
if you have chosen the option by mistake.
@endnode
@node SAVE "Instructions - Save League"

   Self Explanatory. Simply type in a filename or select an existing 
file to overwrite. Alternatively, you can Cancel.
NOTE: An ASCII Save Occurs Automatically to the SuperLeague3.51 directory,
with the  name being the League title with '.asc' bolted on.
	e.g  'FA Carling Premiership.Asc' would appear.
@endnode
@node PREFS "Instructions - Preferences"

   Pretty much Self Explanatory, although it should be pointed out that
the option 'Use' on the title bar will NOT Cancel changes made.
Save will save the prefs as they appear at that time, then exit to main
menu ; Use will Exit to Main Menu USING the settings as they have been
altered.
	A quick summary of the options available here :
	    @{b}Ranking system toggle :@{ub} Choose between using goal-difference
		to separate teams on the same points or just goals-scored
		(as in the Football League)
	    @{b}Points for a win toggle :@{ub} 3pts (England) or 2pts (Europe)

	    League Name, Cup filename for this league, User-defined cup,
		Number of teams are all text gadgets which you can alter
		if you wish to change that option.

	    @{b}System Files Reset Facility :@{ub} Primary use is to @{b}INITIALIZE@{ub}
		files for a newly created league (See the 'Creating a new
		League' @{"Tutorial" link TUTORIAL}) but if your existing files get in a
 		real mess and won't work and you want to start again with
		empty, but initialized files then choose this option.
	    @{b}Special Correcting Facility :@{ub} Allows you to correct the data
		in the league table. Unfortunately, this won't alter the
		data in the main database which stores all the results so
		either a) Don't make mistakes or b) If you do, then you can
		tweak the table here but not the results stored in the
		database.
		This feature is particularly useful if a team is deducted
		points for some misdemeanor - but you can't have negative
		points (Hello Spurs fans) for some reason (this is a
		feature* of AMOS Interface - not my fault)
							* = Bug  
	    @{b}Change System Filenames :@{ub} More text gadgets to alter the system
		filenames. Make sure you know what you are doing before you
		change these (See 'Creating a new league' @{"Tutorial" link TUTORIAL}) and be
		careful with the filepaths.
	    @{b}Choose Favourite Team :@{ub} Pick your favourite team in this league
		and confirm it. Easy. 
@endnode
@node PROPTS "Instructions - Print Options Menu Item"

   Allows Printing Of Any League Table Including the One In Memory or one
from an ASCII file (See Save Above). Also allows Printing of the Favourite
team Season Results File.
@endnode
@node ABOUT "Instructions - About Menu Option"

   Information about SuperLeague.
@endnode
@node QUIT "Instructions - Quit"

   Obviously, Quits the system . Requires Confirmation by a Press of 'q'
on the keyboard.
@endnode
@node ENTER "Instructions - Enter Results"

   Input League Results using a point-and-click interface. Simply select
the teams, then input the scores and confirm selection.

N.B. When A Result is input featuring the team selected as 'Favourite',
     SuperLeague will ask for additional information about scorers and 
     goal timings. This Information will then be saved to files.

   Try to Input All the Weekends Results AT ONCE. This will lead to the
correct league position being calculated. Obviously if you were to only
enter the result of your favourite team, and then enter the other results
later, a false position would have been stored in the System 'Position'
file since the favourite team would have played a game more @{b}AT THE TIME@{ub}
the position was calculated. Just to Clarify - The new league position of
the favourite team is calculated and stored when you select EXIT on the
Enter Results Screen.
@endnode
@node CUP "Instructions - Enter Cup Results Menu Item"

   This is to keep up the cup results record of the 'favourite' team
assigned to a particular league. All features are self explanatory.
It should be noted that if the Cup File as defined in preferences does not
exist and this option is selected then you will be given the option to 
initialise that filename. If you do this you will be returned to the
menu screen. Then simply Re-Select the Enter Cup Results option and all will
be well. You should not enter results if you do not wish them to remain on
file. It is not possible to erase stored data from SuperLeague once it has
been confirmed and saved to disk.
@endnode
@node NAMES "Instructions - Change Team Names"

   Self-Explanatory. The Teams names are not saved by themselves, but
as part of a league table. Hence if you change the team names and wish them
to remain when you reload, you will have to save the current league table
which will store the new names along with it. To automatically load it on
bootup, the appropriate Prefs Option will have to be set to the particular
filename you save under. Default names are those of the 1994-5 FA Premier.
@endnode
@node TABLE "Instructions - View League Table"
   Shows the Current Table in Memory. Clicking on the title bar reveals
the points for a win in this league and the goal difference ranking system.
i.e In the Football League goal-difference is irrelavent, it is only based
on goals scored. A further option is just for interest - to see what the 
table would be under the 'other' points for a win system. In other words, 
if you have a 3 points-for-a-win league in memory then the 'Other Table'
option would show you what the table would look like under a 2 points for a
win system.
@endnode
@node FAVE "Instructions - Favourite Team Results"

   Shows the Season Results file, and the home and away records for the
season. The Results list is operated by a slider, but this is automatically
scaled so that if you click on the slider bar ABOVE or BELOW the 'position
box' (red blob) then it will move the display five lines up or down -
ie. 1 match worth up or down. This keeps things neat as you don't have the
odd scorers name hanging around at the top of the window without being able
to see which match he scored in.
@endnode
@node FORM "Instructions - Favourite Team Form"

   Shows the last 5 results of the favourite team and calculates a form
rating based on these.

@endnode
@node GRAPH "Instructions - View Position Graph"

   Draws a graph to show the fluctuations the favourite team's league
position over the season.
@endnode
@node BARCHART "Instructions - View Goal Timings Chart"

   Creates a Bar Chart to show the number of goals your favourite team has
scored in various time intervals in their games.
@endnode
@node ATTDEF "Instructions - Attacking / Defending Chart"

   Shows a list of the top attacking and defensive teams in the league
currently in memory.
@endnode
@node AV "Instructions - View Averages"

   Shows several ranked lists of the current teams in memory based on goals
per game (both scored and conceded) and points per game.
@endnode
@node GD "Instructions - Goal difference List"
   Shows a ranked list of the best and worst goal differences of the 
teams in the current league in memory.
@endnode
@node CLOCK "Instructions - Clock and Date"

   Assuming you have an Internal clock in your Amiga, and the time has been
correctly set from it in the startup-sequence via Setclock , then this menu
item keeps track of the current time. It will not be updated while you
watch, but every time the menu bar is called up by pressing the right mouse
button, it will show the latest time.
@endnode	
@node HISTORY "SuperLeague History"

@{b}V3.51@{ub}     -   PD
   A minor update to V3.50, the only difference being that this version is
@{b}Hard Disk@{ub} installable. All previous releases V3.40,V3.41,V3.50 are
unfortunately NOT hard disk installable.


@{b}V3.50@{ub}     -   PD
   Basically this version is a bug fix to plug the gap between the previous
release SuperLeague V3.41 and the registered version of the program -
SuperLeague V3.51.

Bugs fixed : 
 
   1)   Print routines now Work !!!!!!  I had no printer access before
       and could not test the print routines but now have, and have
       corrected the bugs that I found.

   2)   Scorers data storage on the Season Results file now works
       without hiccups. Previously someones name might appear twice
       when it shouldn't have. 

   3)   Cup Results Bug. Previously on viewing the FA Cup results (say)
       and exiting to view the Coca-Cola results (say), some of the
       FA cup results would be left on the display. This is now corrected.
	
   4)   Saved ASCII file now ranked properly.
	


@{b}V3.41@{ub}     -   PD
   A minor update to 3.40 but I can't remember what the difference was !!


@{b}V3.40@{ub}     -   PD
   The first public release, first sent to NBS in Nov 93 and uploaded to
the Aminet in February 94. It worked..... just not very well : Print
routines didn't work :( and like all versions prior to v3.51 it was not HD
installable. Compared to V3.51 it's a bit crap really. Still everyone's got
to start somewhere.


@{b}V2.20@{ub}     -    NEVER RELEASED
   Written in AmigaBASIC (Look, I'd just got my Amiga and it was better than
Spectrum basic, OK ?) and it featured menus as a front end to version 1
plus a few minor statistics features.

@{b}V1.00@{ub}     -    NEVER IN DANGER OF BEING RELEASED
   Also written in AmigaBASIC about 5 days before starting on version 2 it
was entirely keyboard operated. And not very good. Still it spawned quite a
monster as anyone who has read this far will testify.
@endnode
@node TUTORIAL "Creating a new league : A Tutorial"

   Already provided on the disk are files sufficient to allow you to
immediately start maintaining your own FA Carling Premiership League Table.
However, if you are Scottish , Welsh , Estonian...... etc you will
probably wish to ignore this and create your own new League.
This document traces this through step-by-step in order for you to get
acquainted with the method involved.

   When you first boot-up, the 'FA Carling Premiership' will already be
loaded - at first it is blank. If you wish to get it up to date you can use
the 'Special Team Data Correcting Facility' from the @{"Preferences" link PREFS} screen.
The default 'Favourite Team' is @{"Leeds United" link LEEDS} (Because they're the best...
I think I'll just say hello to the Internet Whites at this point ;-) )
but you can easily change this, also from the Preferences Screen, by
selecting the @{b}'Select Favourite Team'@{ub} Option. When you have things as you
want them, just save the league to disk by using the Save League option from
the first menu on the main screen. This is wise at any time you make an
alteration to the Preferences which is particular to any league, since many
Preferences settings are saved along with league data. So even if you
haven't changed the actual team data by inputting any new results, but
you have changed the name of one of the System files pertaining to that 
table, you should save the league to ensure that change is made permanent.
This applies to any league.

@{b}Making a Different League Appear Automatically on Bootup :@{ub}

Simply input the name of the file, into the @{b}'League Table to load on
Bootup'@{ub} option in the Preferences screen, including the path which will
usually be 'Leagues/' since by default this is where league files are
saved. You should then save preferences settings by clicking on the save
option in the top right-hand corner of the Preferences screen.

@{b}Creating a Brand New League :@{ub}

The following example is for creating Endsleigh Division 2 from when you
first bootup :

1) The default league in memory is the FA Carling Premiership which only
has 22 teams while Division 2 has 24 teams. Hence you should first select
Preferences from the first menu, and change the @{b}'Number of Teams'@{ub} input
zone to 24. Also change the text in the @{b}'League Name'@{ub} box to "Endsleigh
Division 2" or something similar. Then select @{b}'Use'@{ub} to return to the menu
screen.

2) Select @{b}'Change Team Names'@{ub} from the Second Menu. Change all the team
names to all those in Division 2. Note that two boxes should have 'No Name'
written in them. These are the two extra which did not exist in the
Premiership. You should rename all the boxes them to the relavent teams from
Division 2. Then select Exit.

3) Decide which Team in Division 2 is your favourite, whose Results you
wish to keep track of. Now Select Preferences again.

4) Select @{b}'Choose Favourite Team'@{ub} and click on the relavent team which you
just decided on. Now Click on the @{b}'Confirm List Selection'@{ub} button. If your
selection was correct, select the @{b}'OK'@{ub} box. Now select Exit to return to the
main prefs screen. 

5) The Football League do not employ the goal-difference system to separate
teams on the same points, but look at goals scored only. Hence change the
@{b}'Goal difference Ranking System'@{ub} button so that it reads @{b}'Gs For'@{ub}(Goals For)

6) Change the @{b}'Default Cup Data File'@{ub} filename to something relavent to your
team. For instance, if you support Stockport County you could have the
filename  'SuperLeague:Cups/94_95.SCFC'. Personalisation like this is
recommended to avoid clashes between the cup files for different leagues.

7) Similarly we need to change the System Data files for this league to 
something specifically identifiable and unique to this league to avoid 
clashes. Select @{b}'Change System Data Filenames'@{ub}. Now Change all the filenames
which read SysFiles/PremXXXXX.data according to which file is doing what.
It makes sense to change them all from SysFiles/PremXXXXX.data to
SysFiles/Div2XXXXX.data.   (For Division 2)
   So for instance, Change the filename for the goal timings data from
'SysFiles/PremTimings.data' to 'SysFiles/Div2Timings.data' and repeat
this for the rest. Then select exit to return to the main prefs screen.

9) Now we need to initialize these new files so they are ready for use.
Select the @{b}'System File Reset Facility'@{ub} button. Click on the upper
@{b}'Reset/Initialize System Files'@{ub} button. When disk activity has finished,
click on @{b}Exit@{ub} to return to the main Prefs screen.

10) Click on @{b}Save@{ub}, to save the new settings and to return to the Main Menu

11) Now we must save the league, even though it is empty - mainly to
preserve some of the Division 2 specific preferences data we have entered.
To do this , select @{b}'Save League'@{ub} from the first menu. Input a relavent
filename such as @{b}'Division2'@{ub} and click on @{b}'OK'@{ub}. 

This will make the league perfectly usuable. Select @{b}'View League Table'@{ub} from
Menu 3 to see the table. To enter results , select @{b}'Enter League Results'@{ub}
from Menu 2. Make sure you know who scored for your favourite team and in
what minute before you enter one of their results !!

12) (Optional)
   If you want to update the league to the current real life position, you
have 2 options. First , you could enter every result from the start :( 
(Not a good idea unless you are masochistic)
More likely though, you won't want to do this, so you can select the 
@{b}'Special Team Data Correcting Facility'@{ub} from the Prefs Screen, and alter all
the team data. This of course will mean that your System files will not
carry the results of all the teams for the season that had passed before 
you started using SuperLeague, and so you will not have a totally
comprehensive league position graph or season results facility, and nor will
the results and scorers of all your favourite team's results be present
on file.

When you have finished updating, don't forget to save.


@{b}VERY IMPORTANT

NEVER NEVER NEVER forget to save the league after entering any results!!@{ub}
If you do forget, and find yourself re-entering the result, the
result data will be saved @{b}TWICE@{ub} to the relavent system files and the
result will appear twice in the form guide, Season Results List, and the 
goal timings will be counted twice.
@endnode
@node LEEDS "Leeds United AFC"

    Bloody good when they play well and damn frustrating when they don't.
Things are looking up though as we have a young team in the right places 
which will improve and should be in contention in the next few seasons. With
the best right-back in Eur...well maybe soon but certainly the UK in Gary
Kelly and one of the most underrated emerging young central defenders in
David Wetherall plus the electric Rodney "Goal of the Season" Wallace and
the continuing brilliance of Gary McAllister, Tony Dorigo, Gary Speed and
John Lukic ;-) we will take some stopping. We finished 5th last year, so if
Brian Deane scores some goals this time we'll take the Premiership by storm.
@endnode
